Flows (ServiceNow)
🔹 What are Flows?

Flows in ServiceNow are automated workflows created using Flow Designer to execute tasks and business processes with low-code/no-code development.

Flows help automate activities across applications without extensive scripting.

🔹 Features
Low-code / No-code automation
Trigger-based execution
Drag-and-drop configuration
Integration with multiple applications
Supports approvals and notifications
🔹 Components of Flow
1. Trigger

Defines when the flow starts.

Examples:

Record created
Record updated
Scheduled execution
2. Actions

Tasks performed after the trigger executes.

Examples:

Create record
Send notification
Update record
Request approval
3. Flow Logic

Controls execution path and decision-making.

Examples:

If condition
Wait for condition
Loop actions
4. Data Pills

Used to pass information between triggers and actions.

🔹 Types of Triggers
Record Trigger
Application Trigger
Schedule Trigger
Service Catalog Trigger
🔹 Flow Process

Trigger
↓
Condition
↓
Action Execution
↓
Complete Flow

🔹 Benefits
Reduces manual work
Improves process efficiency
Minimizes scripting effort
Faster automation deployment
🔹 Example

Scenario:
When an Incident is created →
Automatically assign group →
Send notification →
Update status.

🔹 Flow vs Workflow
Flow	Workflow
Modern automation	Legacy automation
Low-code design	More scripting
Uses Flow Designer	Uses Workflow Editor
Easy integration	Traditional process design
